Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["Summary Remarks Concerning the Separation Method",
 FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]], "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.395592975204886*^9, 3.39559301272864*^9}}],

Cell["\<\
The following remarks are of general significance, but will be phrased as \
they relate to our experience with the drum problem:\
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] Separation proceeded from a strong ",
 StyleBox["factorization assumption",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.3955931517793417`*^9, 3.3955931546945343`*^9}}],

Cell[BoxData[
 StyleBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"u", "[", 
    RowBox[{"r", ",", "\[Theta]", ",", "t"}], "]"}], "=", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"R", "[", "r", "]"}], "*", 
    RowBox[{"A", "[", "\[Theta]", "]"}], "*", 
    RowBox[{"f", "[", "t", "]"}]}]}], "Output",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0.5]]], "Input"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "and led to ",
 StyleBox["particular",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
 " solutions of the PDE in question.  But the general solution (it could be \
shown) can be developed as a ",
 StyleBox["linear combination (superposition) of those particular solutions",
  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]],
 "."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.396094112941374*^9, 3.396094118766603*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 StyleBox["Spectral discreteness arose",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
 " not from the PDE itself (which speaks in the language of smooth variation) \
but ",
 StyleBox["from the associated boundary conditions",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
 ". It is from this same circumstance that quantum mechanics acquires the \
quantal discreteness to which its name refers, and so does music."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.395593207904147*^9, 3.395593217059717*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " made duck soup of the computational/graphic details, but ",
 StyleBox["we ourselves were responsible for the controlling ideas",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
 "\[LongDash]responsible, in particular, for the decision to work in polar \
coordinates."
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] The decision to work in polar coordinates served us in two \
distinct ways: (1) it ",
 StyleBox["permitted separation of the PDE",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
 ", and (2) it ",
 StyleBox["permitted natural description of the boundary conditions",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
 ".  The theory in hand could be adapted to a theory of wedge-shaped \
drumheads (more generally: any drumheads bounded by arcs of constant r and \
arcs of constant \[Theta]), but it has nothing to say about (say) elliptical \
drums, or annular drumheads with off-center holes."
}], "Text"],

Cell["\<\
\[Bullet] All strings have the same shape, and support therefore similar sets \
of harmonics. But drumheads (2-dimensional systems) can have an infinite \
variety of shapes, and each supports its own distinct  set of harmonics. It \
becomes plausibe to speculate that one can \"hear the shape of a drum.\"\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.39559337541936*^9, 3.3955934522073317`*^9}, {
  3.3955934900941277`*^9, 3.39559353440847*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\[Bullet] Our ability to adapt the separation of variables method to other \
physical problems is limited by our ",
 StyleBox["command of separating coordinate systems",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
 ", and we can expect in all events to be able to deal only with systems in \
which the ",
 StyleBox["boundaries conform to the geometry",
  FontColor->RGBColor[0, 0, 1]],
 " of whatever coordinate system we have selected. (In other\[LongDash]more \
general cases\[LongDash]we would have to fall back on numerical methods which \
are a vast subject in themselves.)"
}], "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "\tThe latter circumstance has\[LongDash]more than any \
other\[LongDash]inspired development of a great number of wonderful \
coordinate systems, about which ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " knows a great deal. Moreover, variable-separation procedures, carried out \
in those diverse coordinate systems, have inspired the invention and study of \
many of the \"higher transcendental functions\" (things like the Bessel \
functions encountered above) that are the bread & butter of mathematical \
physics, and about which ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " also knows a great deal."
}], "Text"],

Cell["", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.395593703649667*^9, 3.3955937037455263`*^9}}],

Cell["", "Text"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

